The root cause of the null dereference is that `type` can be NULL when passed to `method_get`, but the code does not check for this before calling `PyType_Check(type)`. This leads to a NULL pointer dereference in the macro expansion of `PyType_Check`, which ultimately tries to access `type->ob_type`.

**Patch Plan:**
- Add a check for `type == NULL` before calling `PyType_Check(type)` in `method_get`.
- If `type` is NULL, raise a `TypeError` with an appropriate message and return NULL.

Let's generate the patch.
```diff
--- a/Objects/descrobject.c
+++ b/Objects/descrobject.c
@@ -147,10 +147,17 @@
     if (descr->d_method->ml_flags & METH_METHOD) {
-        if (PyType_Check(type)) {
-            return PyCMethod_New(descr->d_method, obj, NULL, descr->d_common.d_type);
-        } else {
-            PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
-                        "descriptor '%V' needs a type, not '%s', as arg 2",
-                        descr_name((PyDescrObject *)descr),
-                        Py_TYPE(type)->tp_name);
-            return NULL;
-        }
+        if (type == NULL) {
+            PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
+                         "descriptor '%V' needs a type as arg 2, got NULL",
+                         descr_name((PyDescrObject *)descr));
+            return NULL;
+        }
+        if (PyType_Check(type)) {
+            return PyCMethod_New(descr->d_method, obj, NULL, descr->d_common.d_type);
+        } else {
+            PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
+                        "descriptor '%V' needs a type, not '%s', as arg 2",
+                        descr_name((PyDescrObject *)descr),
+                        Py_TYPE(type)->tp_name);
+            return NULL;
+        }
     } else {
         return PyCFunction_NewEx(descr->d_method, obj, NULL);
     }
```

